{% block instructions %}
You are the **synthesis** author. Mechanical work (extraction,
classification, atomic page rendering) is already done. The
replica directory at `{{ run.replica_root }}` contains every atomic
page the source contributed. Your job is to add 1–2 synthesis
pages.

Each synthesis page is a **stand-alone wiki entry on a synthesized
topic**: it describes the topic on its own terms and uses the
materialized atomic pages (people, models, keywords, …) as
supporting links. It is NOT an index, commentary, or companion to
the source — the source is a citation, not the subject.

Ultrathink about which kinds cluster into a shared topic before
committing to a page split. Over-fragmentation is the most common
failure mode — prefer one rich page over two thin ones.

## Read first

1. Read each peer's ``task_path`` file. Each file's payload is a
   YAML object with one top-level key (the peer kind) holding a
   list of items. Each item has at minimum a ``name``; other
   fields vary by kind.
2. Read each peer's ``verdict_path`` file. Each carries
   ``item_verdicts`` — an array of
   ``{target, verdict, scores, rationale}``. Items with REJECT
   verdicts SHOULD be omitted; REVIEW items can be included
   with caution.
3. List the replica directory `{{ run.replica_root }}` to see which
   atomic pages already exist as standalone files. Wikilinks
   (``[[Atomic Name]]``) MUST point at filenames that exist
   there OR at ``### Name`` subsections you will create on the
   same synthesis page (``[[#Name]]``).

## Voice and framing

The page is a wiki entry on its own topic, not commentary on the
source it draws from. Concretely:

- **Open with the topic, not the page.** Do NOT use phrases like
  "this hub orbits…", "this companion hub turns…", "this page
  covers…", "this article presents…". Open by stating what the
  topic *is* and why it matters.
- **Describe the topic on its own terms.** Treat materialized
  atomic pages (people, models, keywords) as supporting links —
  reach for ``[[Person Name]]`` when the person is factually
  relevant, not as the page's organizing center. Do not write
  "Author X's three case studies" when "Three observed cases"
  reads more cleanly.
- **Do not center the source.** Phrases like "the article's
  central thesis", "the article's negative case", "the source
  argues" reframe the page as commentary on a document. Make
  the same point directly ("The central claim is…", "The
  negative case is…") and let the source/author appear as
  wikilinks in supporting clauses.
- **Cite, don't narrate.** The source goes in the ``sources``
  frontmatter field and may appear as a ``[[Source Title]]``
  wikilink where natural. Do not paraphrase the source's
  rhetorical structure.
- **Multi-source futureproofing.** A topic may later be revisited
  by other sources; write prose that survives that — describe
  the topic, attribute specific framings to specific people via
  wikilinks rather than to "the source".

## Coverage obligations

- **1–2 pages total.** Merge overlapping topics; do NOT produce
  one page per cluster. Over-fragmentation fails the judge.
- **Synthesis-mode kinds MUST be folded inline.** Every kind
  whose ``destinations.<kind>.mode == 'synthesis'`` (e.g.
  ``topics``, ``themes``, ``key_points``, ``chapters``) has NO
  standalone vault page. EVERY item from those kinds MUST
  appear in some page's ``key_concepts`` array as
  ``mode: 'included'``. If you can't justify including an item,
  the item is unused — that's a coverage failure.
- **Artifact-mode kinds (e.g. ``keywords``, ``people``,
  ``models``) already have standalone replica pages.** Either
  ``mode: 'connected'`` (link to the standalone page) or
  ``mode: 'included'`` (fold inline; the standalone page still
  stands) is fine.

## Authoring + rendering protocol

For each page you author, build a JSON file with the structured
fields the wiki template requires, then run the renderer to
turn it into markdown. The renderer (``render.sh`` from the
``template`` skill) uses ``StrictUndefined`` and refuses to
render if any field is missing — this is the enforcement
mechanism. Do not skip fields; supply empty values
(``""`` or ``[]``) for genuinely-absent optional fields.

### Step 1 — author the JSON

For each page, write a JSON file at ``/tmp/<slug>.json``:

```json
{
  "title":          "Topic Title",
  "today":          "<YYYY-MM-DD today>",
  "sources":        ["10 SOURCES/Articles/<source-basename>"],
  "rationale":      "Opening paragraph (≥80 chars) introducing the topic on its own terms. Sits before ## Overview. Do NOT narrate the page's structure or reference 'this hub'/'this page'/'this article'; describe the topic.",
  "overview":       "Multi-paragraph prose (≥200 chars) describing the topic. Wikilinks on first occurrence of every atomic name. Treat the source as a citation target (frontmatter + wikilinks), not as the subject of the prose.",
  "ascii_diagram":  "Multi-line illustrative diagram (≥4 lines, ≥80 chars).\nUse box-drawing chars: ┌ ┐ └ ┘ │ ─ ┬ ┴ ├ ┤ ┼ ▼ ▲ ◄ ►",
  "key_concepts":   [
    {"name": "Atomic A", "mode": "included",  "summary": "Inline definition (≥30 chars)."},
    {"name": "Atomic B", "mode": "connected", "summary": "Orientation pointing at [[Atomic B]]'s standalone page."},
    {"name": "Atomic C", "mode": "included",  "summary": "Another inline definition."}
  ],
  "see_also":       [
    {"name": "Related Topic or Atomic", "kind": "atomic", "note": "optional"}
  ],
  "worked_examples": [],
  "discussion":      ""
}
```

Required: ``title``, ``today``, ``sources``, ``rationale``,
``overview``, ``ascii_diagram``, ``key_concepts`` (≥3 entries,
each with ``name``/``mode``/``summary``), ``see_also``.
``worked_examples`` and ``discussion`` are optional but MUST be
present (empty array / empty string) — the renderer fails on
missing keys.

### Step 2 — render to the replica

Run the wiki renderer; pipe stdout into the replica file. Use
the **natural title verbatim** as the filename (with filesystem-
illegal chars stripped — strip ``: * ? " < > |`` and replace
``/`` with ``—``). DO NOT kebab-case the filename. Obsidian
resolves wikilinks like ``[[Topic Title]]`` against the filename
directly:

```bash
$SKILLS/home/template/scripts/render.sh \
    --template {{ templates.wiki_template_path }} \
    --include-dir {{ templates.vault_templates_dir }} \
    --json-vars /tmp/<slug>.json \
    --allow-unused \
    > "{{ run.replica_root }}/21 SYNTHESIS/<Topic Title>.md"
```

Example: a page titled ``Constraining LLM Coding Agents`` lands
at ``{{ run.replica_root }}/21 SYNTHESIS/Constraining LLM Coding Agents.md``.

If the renderer prints
``ERROR: template variables not provided: <name>`` on stderr,
add the missing key to your JSON (with an empty value if it's
genuinely absent) and re-run. **Do not edit the rendered
markdown by hand** — fix the JSON and re-render. The template
is the source of truth for the layout.

### Step 3 — record the path

After each page renders successfully, record its vault-relative
path in your output:

```bash
curator.sh builders add {{ task.output_path }} \
    --set paths.<i>='21 SYNTHESIS/<Topic Title>.md'
```

Increment ``<i>`` per page (0, 1) — cap at 2.

If you wrote zero pages (the source genuinely has no topics
worth a stand-alone wiki entry), leave ``paths`` empty:

```bash
curator.sh builders add {{ task.output_path }} --set paths='[]'
```

## Inline wikilink discipline

Inside ``rationale``, ``overview``, ``key_concepts.<i>.summary``,
``worked_examples.<i>.body``, and ``discussion``, the FIRST
occurrence of any atomic name MUST be wrapped as a wikilink:

- connected atomic → ``[[Atomic Name]]``
- included atomic on this page → ``[[#Atomic Name]]``
- atomic on another synthesis page → ``[[Atomic Name]]``

Subsequent occurrences need not be wrapped.
